TASK 1A REVIEW — COMPLETE

Findings (most severe first):

1. [SIGNIFICANT] OAuthSessionBinding (backend/app/middleware/session.py)
   has no expiry sweep, only lazy expiry-on-resolve. `store()` inserts into
   an in-process dict keyed by request_token with no cap and no background
   cleanup; an entry for a request-token whose callback is never completed
   (abandoned handshake, or a client that calls `/zotero/auth/start`
   repeatedly without following through) sits in `_pending` forever, since
   the TTL is only checked reactively inside `resolve()`, never proactively
   swept. Concrete failure scenario: a low-effort scripted client that
   repeatedly hits `/zotero/auth/start` (this task doesn't own inbound
   rate-limiting — that's a separate Wave 2/3D concern — but the primitive
   itself provides no self-bounding) accumulates unbounded entries in a
   single always-on process (§12.2) that's never restarted; this is a slow
   memory-exhaustion vector against the only backend process the whole app
   runs on. This is exactly the failure class BuildPlan's own review
   prompt calls out ("does it leak memory if bindings are never claimed —
   no expiry sweep?") and the answer is yes. Not blocking Wave 2's start
   per se, since 1C's happy-path use of `store`/`resolve` is otherwise
   correct (verified in test_oauth_session_binding.py: mismatch, replay,
   single-use, and expiry are all genuinely tested), but should be fixed
   before this ships to a real always-on deployment — either evict expired
   entries opportunistically inside `store()` (cheap: iterate and drop
   `expires_at < now` on every insert) or accept the memory cost is bounded
   by realistic traffic and document that trade-off explicitly (it
   currently isn't documented at all, unlike the other two trade-offs in
   this file which are explicitly called out).

2. [SIGNIFICANT] Fernet/cookie-secret ephemeral-fallback is a silent-until-
   restart data-loss trap with only a log-line safeguard, no hard fail-fast
   for production. Both `crypto.py::_get_key` and `session.py::_get_cookie_
   secret` fall back to a per-process-random key when the env var is
   unset, logged via `logger.warning(...)` only. There is no environment-
   aware check (e.g. refusing to boot, or escalating to `logger.critical`/
   raising, when running outside a recognized dev/test context) that would
   force an operator to notice before the first restart silently and
   irrecoverably invalidates every previously-encrypted `ZoteroConnection.
   oauth_token`/`oauth_token_secret` row (Fernet tokens encrypted under a
   discarded ephemeral key can never be decrypted again — this is
   permanent data loss, not a recoverable error) and, for the cookie
   secret, silently logs every returning user out (a UX papercut, lower
   stakes, but same root cause). A log line in a hosting platform's log
   stream (Render, per §12.2) is easy to miss entirely if nobody is
   actively tailing logs at deploy time — by the time someone notices
   (users reporting "Zotero disconnected again" after a routine redeploy),
   the damage from the *previous* restart is already unrecoverable. This
   doesn't block Wave 2 (which only needs the primitive to work in dev/
   test, where the fallback is genuinely fine and correctly documented as
   such), but it is a real operational landmine that whoever owns
   deployment (Tier 5, per config.py's own comment) needs to close before
   any real deployment — e.g. a startup check that hard-fails when
   `ENVIRONMENT=production` and either secret is unset, rather than
   relying on someone reading a warning log at the right moment.

3. [MINOR] No `UniqueConstraint`/composite-unique index on `(session_id,
   pmid)` for `QueueDecision`, despite SPEC.md §9.2 describing it as "one
   row per (search session, paper) pair" — confirmed by grepping entities.py
   (only `ZoteroConnection.session_id` and `SearchSession.session_id` carry
   `unique=True`; `QueueDecision`/`ZoteroExport` only have non-unique
   `index=True` on `session_id` and `pmid` separately). Nothing at the
   model layer prevents a future caller (Wave 2's route handlers) from
   inserting two `QueueDecision` rows for the same `(session_id, pmid)`,
   which would make later code (e.g. `PATCH /api/v1/decisions/{pmid}`,
   §10.4) ambiguous about which row to update, and could let the Saved
   List Panel double-count a paper. This isn't a session-confusion issue
   (session scoping itself is fine) and isn't itself exploitable by an
   attacker without a code bug elsewhere, so it's minor rather than
   significant — but it's a real gap against §9.2's own wording, worth
   1B/1D/whoever writes queue-insert logic knowing about, since 1A's model
   layer won't catch the mistake for them.

4. [MINOR] `ZoteroConnection.oauth_token`/`oauth_token_secret` are plain
   `str` columns with no model-level mechanism (custom SQLAlchemy type,
   validator, or property) that would force encryption before writes reach
   the column — encryption is entirely a call-site discipline convention
   documented in a docstring ("Use `encrypt_token`/`decrypt_token` at the
   call site... rather than reaching into these columns directly"). §9.6's
   requirement is satisfied *if* Task 1C's OAuth callback (not yet built)
   respects this convention, but nothing in 1A's own layer would catch a
   regression where 1C (or a later refactor) accidentally stores plaintext
   directly. Not blocking 1A's own merge (1A does exactly what it was
   asked to build), but worth 1C's own review specifically re-checking
   that the callback handler actually calls `encrypt_token` before
   constructing the row, since there's no structural guardrail forcing it.

No blocking findings — I disagree with tester's "no findings at all,
even minor" framing (tester's log explicitly says so) on points 1-4 above,
but agree with tester's core verdict that the security-critical primitives
this checkpoint exists to gate — CSPRNG session_id generation, rotation-on-
Zotero-connect actually invalidating the old id (not just adding a new one
alongside it), HttpOnly/Secure/SameSite=None cookie issuance, constant-time
comparison via `hmac.compare_digest`/`secrets.compare_digest` everywhere a
secret is compared, and the OAuth binding primitive's mismatch/expiry/
single-use rejection — are all genuinely, not superficially, implemented
and tested. Tier 1 Wave 2 (1B/1C/1D) is safe to start against this as a
merged dependency; findings 1-2 should be filed as follow-up work (ideally
before Tier 5 deployment, not necessarily before Wave 2) and finding 4
flagged specifically to whoever reviews Task 1C's OAuth callback.

