[2026-07-04T15:35:00] TASK 2D REVIEW — PIVOT
Built a throwaway repro test (frontend/src/playback/_race_repro*.test.ts,
deleted after use, never committed) to test tester's specific hypothesis:
delayed/unawaited `requestWakeLock()` promise racing state updates in the
mute test. Ran the actual mute test 50x back-to-back (x4 = 200 runs) and
the full suite 56x (28+28, one batch cut short by a tool timeout, not by
a failure) — zero reproductions of tester's "expected 'title' to be
'seg-0'" failure. Reading play()'s wake-lock `.then()` callback shows it
only ever does `wakeLockRef.current = lock` (a plain ref write) or
`lock?.release()` — it never calls any React state setter
(setStatus/setCurrentKey/setUsingFallbackTimer), so there is no code path
by which its resolution timing could change `currentKey`. This refutes
tester's specific causal chain as stated, even though the underlying
"unawaited promise" code smell is real. This redirected my race-condition
investigation toward constructing my own repro instead, which found a
different, deterministic (not flaky) bug in the same function: calling
`play()` twice synchronously in one `act()`/event-handler tick (e.g. a
double-tap/double-click on the play button) produces 2 real `speak()`
calls for the same item, confirmed 100% reproducible in a standalone
test (`speakSpy.length === 2` when 1 was expected). Root cause: the
`if (status === "playing") return` guard reads component state (`status`)
which has not yet committed after the first call's `setStatus("playing")`
in the same synchronous batch, so a second call in the same tick sees
the same stale value and passes the guard; `generationRef` (a ref, correctly
synchronous) is bumped and does prevent the *stale* utterance's onend/onerror
from advancing state, but does nothing to stop the *second* call from
firing its own real `env.synth.speak()` — so the browser still queues and
audibly speaks the current item twice in a row.

[2026-07-04T15:40:00] TASK 2D REVIEW — COMPLETE
Findings, most severe first:

1. SIGNIFICANT — confirmed via reproducible test, not theoretical.
   `usePlaybackEngine.ts`'s `play()` (lines 287-299) guards re-entrancy
   with `if (status === "playing") return`, where `status` is React
   state read from the closure, not a ref. Two synchronous invocations
   of `play()` within the same event-handler tick (concrete trigger:
   a double-tap/double-click on the play button, or two rapid Space
   keypresses processed before React commits `setStatus("playing")`)
   both see the pre-update `status` value and both pass the guard. Each
   call independently bumps `generationRef.current` and calls
   `playItem(indexRef.current, generation)`, and since `indexRef.current`
   hasn't advanced between the two calls, both create a real utterance
   for the *same* item and both call `env.synth.speak()`. The
   generation-counter guard correctly makes the first utterance's
   `onend`/`onerror` a no-op (so internal state doesn't corrupt/skip
   items), but it does nothing to stop the second `speak()` call itself
   — a real speechSynthesis engine would audibly narrate the current
   item twice in a row. Reproduced in an isolated throwaway test (not
   committed): `speakSpy.length === 2` after `act(() => { play(); play(); })`
   with a single hook instance. This is exactly the class of "rapid
   play/cancel/play" race the review brief asked about, and the
   generation-counter guard genuinely does not close this specific gap
   because both calls pass the `status` check before either commits.
   Not blocking (no crash, no security issue, no permanent desync —
   playback still recovers and completes correctly from item 1 onward)
   but real and user-triggerable. Recommend the guard be based on a ref
   (e.g. check/set a `isPlayingRef` synchronously at the top of `play()`)
   rather than the React `status` state value.

2. SIGNIFICANT (partially refutes, partially confirms tester's own
   flake finding) — tester's "TASK 2B VERIFY" entry reports a 1/12
   intermittent full-suite failure in the mute test
   ("advances the highlight on the exact same clock whether muted or
   not"), hypothesized to be caused by the unawaited
   `requestWakeLock().then(...)` promise in `play()` racing state
   updates. I attempted extensive independent reproduction: the mute
   test run back-to-back 200x (4 batches of 50), the full suite run 56x,
   and a custom repro forcing the wake-lock promise to resolve at
   adversarial points relative to the manual clock — zero reproductions
   of tester's specific failure. More importantly, reading the `.then()`
   callback shows it only performs `wakeLockRef.current = lock` (a plain
   ref write, not a React state setter) or `lock?.release()` — there is
   no code path by which this callback's timing could change
   `currentKey`, which is what the failing assertion checked. Tester's
   specific causal chain ("unawaited wake-lock promise races the
   manual-clock timer firing" and thereby flips `currentKey`) does not
   hold up under code-level scrutiny or repro attempts, and should not
   be treated as a confirmed root cause. That said, the underlying code
   smell (a fire-and-forget `void promise.then(...)` inside a hook,
   with no test ever awaiting/flushing it) is real and worth fixing for
   test hygiene regardless (it can trigger spurious React "not wrapped
   in act" warnings), and I cannot rule out that tester's original 1/12
   observation was a genuine but differently-caused flake (e.g.
   worker-pool scheduling noise on that machine) rather than a pure
   fluke — I flag this as unresolved rather than dismissed, and
   recommend the specialist not treat "likely source" in their own log
   as settled without a reproducible regression test, since I could not
   produce one despite deliberate effort.

3. MINOR — reporting/documentation gap, not a code bug: tester's own
   "TASK 2D VERIFY — COMPLETE" log entry (the section that renders the
   formal "Task 2D checkpoint MET" verdict) makes no mention of the
   flake at all; it is filed instead under the separate "TASK 2B VERIFY"
   entry logged afterward, discovered incidentally while chasing an
   unrelated 2B discrepancy. A reader relying solely on the "TASK 2D
   VERIFY" section (the one this review was pointed at) would have no
   idea the suite has ever shown non-determinism in this exact file.
   The information isn't lost, just mis-filed under the wrong task's
   verify entry.

4. Duplicated-logic vs. Task 1D (the checkpoint's primary ask):
   confirmed clean, independently of tester's identical conclusion.
   Read `usePlaybackEngine.ts` in full — it never splits text into
   sentences, never special-cases `Fig.`/`vs.`/`et al.`/`e.g.`/other
   abbreviations, and never decides whether a gap is "structural" or
   "sentence"; it only reads `item.pauseClass` (an opaque
   `"structural" | "sentence"` value per `types.ts`, matching
   CONTRACTS.md §1's pinned `pause_class` category) and maps it to a
   millisecond duration via `pauseDurationMs()`. The only `.split()` in
   the file is `estimateSpeechDurationMs`'s `text.trim().split(/\s+/)`,
   used purely as a word-count heuristic to estimate a fallback-timer
   *duration* — confirmed this never touches sentence boundaries,
   abbreviations, or pause-class assignment; it operates on whatever
   text `item.spokenText` already is, sentence-pre-split or not, and
   produces a duration, not a segmentation decision. No violation.

5. Speed-scaling edge cases (§6.4/§15.9): `utterance.rate` is set once
   at utterance creation from `speedRef.current` and cannot be changed
   for an in-flight browser utterance (a genuine Web Speech API
   constraint, not a bug in this module); `pauseDurationMs`/
   `estimateSpeechDurationMs` are likewise computed fresh per item from
   the live `speedRef.current` at the moment each item starts, so a
   mid-utterance speed change takes effect starting at the *next* item
   rather than retroactively — this is consistent between the real-synth
   and timer-fallback paths (no drift/desync introduced across multiple
   sentences, since each item's duration is computed once from current
   state and never carries error forward). Not a bug; would be worth a
   one-line doc comment noting the "takes effect from the next item"
   behavior, but that's cosmetic.

6. Wake Lock rejection handling (§13.2): `defaultEnv().requestWakeLock`
   wraps the real `navigator.wakeLock.request()` call in try/catch and
   resolves to `null` on any rejection (permission denied, document not
   visible, API absent) — confirmed this cannot throw uncaught; `play()`
   handles a `null` lock gracefully (`wakeLockRef.current = lock` is
   simply `null`, and `releaseWakeLock()` is a no-op if `wakeLockRef.current`
   is null). No crash path found.

7. Listener/memory cleanup: no accumulation issue found. Each
   `SpeechSynthesisUtterance`-like object's `onend`/`onerror` closures
   are scoped to that single utterance instance (referenced transiently
   via `currentUtteranceRef`, replaced on the next item, never pushed to
   a growing collection); the unmount effect (lines 329-337) bumps
   `generationRef`, clears any pending timer, calls `synth?.cancel()`,
   and releases the wake lock, so a component unmount during playback
   cannot leave a "still narrating" utterance whose callbacks later
   mutate state (they'd fail the generation check even if the browser
   still fires them post-unmount). No accumulation across many
   play/cancel cycles found by inspection.

Verdict: Task 2D's core checkpoint (duplicated-logic vs. 1D) is
genuinely clean, matching tester's conclusion — this is not a case of a
wrong "gate met." However, tester's broader "Task 2D checkpoint MET"
verdict rode past a real, deterministically-reproducible race (finding
1) that neither the specialist's log nor tester's targeted 2D-verify
pass caught, because none of the 8 checked-in tests exercise a
same-tick double-invocation of `play()`. I could not substantiate
tester's own specific wake-lock-race hypothesis (finding 2) despite
significant repro effort and reject it as stated, while treating the
underlying flake as still open/unexplained rather than closed. No
blocking findings (no crash, no data corruption, no security issue) —
findings 1 and 2 are significant and should go back to
senior-frontend-developer before this is treated as merge-ready;
findings 3, 5, 6, 7 are minor/informational.

