1. SIGNIFICANT — normalize.py's statistical-notation expansion has no
   handling for ≤/≥ (only ASCII <, >, =), so p-value thresholds written
   with these very common Unicode comparison operators pass through
   completely unexpanded. Confirmed live:
   `normalize_for_speech("p ≤ 0.05 was considered significant.")` returns
   the string unchanged — the ≤ symbol is never converted to "less than
   or equal to" the way §6.3's own worked example does for plain "<".
   This isn't a hypothetical: ≤/≥ p-value notation ("p ≤ 0.001") is at
   least as common in PubMed abstracts as the plain "<" SPEC.md's worked
   example uses, and a TTS engine that silently skips an unrecognized
   Unicode comparison glyph (the exact failure mode §6.3 explicitly
   warns about for Greek letters — "rather than being skipped or read as
   'unknown character' silence") would narrate "p 0.05" with the
   comparison direction lost entirely, changing what the listener
   believes was reported. Not cited by SPEC.md's literal worked examples
   (only <, =, ±, % are enumerated), so this is a coverage gap within
   1D's own declared scope rather than a contradiction of an explicit
   spec line — but it's squarely inside the "Statistical & mathematical
   notation" bullet's stated intent. test_normalize.py has zero cases
   for ≤/≥ (grep confirms). Recommend fixing in 1D now (same three-line
   pattern as the existing </>/= handling) rather than letting it ship;
   cheap, and it's exactly the class of thing that's expensive to
   retrofit once outbound narration behavior is depended on by 2D's
   playback engine.

2. MINOR — the same math-operator regexes (`<\s*(number)`, `>\s*(number)`,
