1. SIGNIFICANT — `_neutralize_formula_injection` (backend/app/routes/export.py:57-64)
   is bypassed by any leading whitespace/control character or invisible
   Unicode character preceding a formula-trigger character. Verified
   directly by calling the function in a REPL:
   `_neutralize_formula_injection("\t=1+1")` -> `"\t=1+1"` (unchanged),
   `_neutralize_formula_injection(" =1+1")` -> `" =1+1"` (unchanged),
   `_neutralize_formula_injection("‮=1+1")` (right-to-left override
   char) -> unchanged. The function only checks `value.startswith(("=",
   "+", "-", "@"))` on the raw string, with no stripping of leading
   whitespace/control/zero-width characters first. This is a real,
   reproducible variant of the exact failure class this review was asked
   to check for (§8.8's own docstring in export.py argues neutralization
   should apply "regardless of how unlikely a hostile PubMed record is in
   practice" — the same logic extends to a title/author string that
   happens to start with a tab or leading space before a trigger char,
   which OWASP's CSV-injection guidance specifically calls out as a
   documented bypass technique against naive startswith-style checks,
   since some spreadsheet CSV importers strip leading whitespace before
   evaluating whether a cell is a formula). None of test_export.py's 4
   parametrized adversarial cases (`=1+1`, `+CMD(...)`, `-2+3+cmd...`,
   `@SUM(...)`) exercise a leading-whitespace or invisible-character
   variant, so this gap has zero test coverage. Concrete trigger: a
   PubMed record with a title field of `"\t=1+1"` (or any leading
   whitespace/zero-width char + trigger char) flows unmodified through
   `_paper_row` into the CSV, and would still render/execute as a formula
   in spreadsheet software that normalizes leading whitespace on import.
   Fix: strip leading whitespace/control characters (or check `value.lstrip()`'s
   first character) before the `startswith` check, and consider stripping
   or flagging leading Unicode format/control characters (Cf category,
   including RTL overrides) as well.

2. Verified, no issue found — CSV row-structure integrity. Confirmed
   directly with `csv.writer` on values containing embedded commas,
   newlines, and quotes: outputs are correctly RFC4180-quoted (e.g.
