   whoever picks up Task 3D's or a later hardening pass.
2. MINOR — Non-atomic two-commit sequence in auth_callback: the new
   ZoteroConnection is inserted and committed under the *old*
   (pre-rotation) session_id, then rotate_session() performs a second,
   separate commit that migrates it onto the new session_id and deletes
   the old Session row. A process crash between these two commits (a
   narrow window, not currently reachable via any tested code path) would
   leave a correctly-encrypted ZoteroConnection persisted under the
   old, not-yet-rotated session_id — reopening the exact session-fixation
   window §9.1/rotate_session exists to close, until the next request
   naturally retries. Purely theoretical (no crash-injection test needed
   to fix; would require wrapping both operations in one transaction/
   savepoint) — noting because it's the one place the "commit, then
   rotate" ordering matters for the property being tested, not because
   there's evidence it's actually been hit.

No blocking or significant findings. The primary ask — session-binding
regression at the route layer — was checked adversarially against the
concrete attack scenario (attacker-initiated handshake + victim tricked
into completing it) and is genuinely closed, both by code inspection and
by a real two-cookie-jar HTTP round-trip test that exercises the actual
route, not just the underlying primitive already covered by Task 1C's
review. Tester's "gate MET" verdict is accurate and its citations were
verified: CONTRACTS.md §4 and SPEC.md §10.4's DELETE row do say what
tester's log claims, and the fixture-shape/idempotency/push-result
assertions cited actually exist in test_zotero_routes.py as described.

