[2026-07-04T21:45:00] TASK 3A REVIEW — COMPLETE

1. SIGNIFICANT — search.py has zero cross-session isolation tests, unlike
   the other three route files. tester's TASK 3A VERIFY/RE-VERIFY rounds
   found and drove fixes for missing cross-session tests in
   test_queue_routes.py, test_saved_routes.py, and
   test_decisions_routes.py, but never flagged that test_search_routes.py
   (grep of its 9 test functions: happy_path, zero_results,
   replaces_prior_queue_decisions, pubmed_unavailable, two validation
   tests, citations_sort, settings_defaults, settings_reflects_last_search)
   has NONE. POST /search and GET /search/settings both read/write
   SearchSession and QueueDecision rows filtered by
   `SearchSession.session_id == session.session_id` /
   `QueueDecision.session_id == session.session_id` (backend/app/routes/
   search.py lines 160-179, 237-239) — by direct code inspection this
   filtering IS correctly present at the SQL WHERE-clause level (not a
   Python post-filter over an over-fetched query), so the current
   behavior looks correct. But it is completely unproven: no test exists
   that would catch a future regression here (e.g. a refactor of the
   select-or-create block that drops the WHERE clause, or one that
   fetches all SearchSession rows and filters in Python instead) — the
   exact same class of gap tester already found and required fixing for
   queue/saved/decisions in this same task was not carried over to the
   fourth file that owns the same kind of session-scoped mutation
   (wiping/rebuilding another session's QueueDecision rows, or reading
   another session's SearchSession settings, would be a real cross-user
   leak/corruption if this filter were ever silently dropped).

2. SIGNIFICANT (scope note: root cause lives in Task 1B's
   app/integrations/pubmed.py, but the risk is realized through 3A's own
   queue.py) — GET /papers/{pmid}/abstract (backend/app/routes/queue.py
   lines 220-230) maps a genuine internal parsing failure to the exact
   same 404 `not_found` response as a truly nonexistent PMID.
   `PubMedClient.efetch()` -> `_parse_efetch_xml()` (app/integrations/
   pubmed.py lines 426-437) wraps `_parse_one_article()` in a broad
   `except Exception` per article, logs at WARNING, and skips it — this
   is individually reasonable (one malformed record shouldn't kill a
   batch, per §7.9), but queue.py's own consumption of the result
   (`if not articles: raise not_found(...)`, line 228-229) cannot
   distinguish "PubMed genuinely has no such PMID" from "every article in
   the batch threw during parsing" (e.g. a real KeyError from an
   unexpected NCBI XML schema change). Concretely: if NCBI changed EFetch's
   XML shape tomorrow such that `_parse_one_article` throws for every
   request, every `/papers/{pmid}/abstract` call would return an
   unremarkable 404 to users, and the server would only log WARNINGs
   (never ERROR/exception-level), meaning nothing in this app's own
   response codes or default log severity would distinguish this from
   normal 404 traffic — hiding a real, systemic backend bug from any
   404-tolerant monitoring/alerting. This is exactly the failure mode
   item 2 of the review brief asked to check for (a genuine internal bug
   misreported as something innocuous instead of surfacing as an error).

3. MINOR — POST /search's select-or-create on `SearchSession`
   (`session_id` is a `unique=True` column, entities.py line ~78) has a
   TOCTOU gap under concurrent double-submit from the same session (e.g.
   a slow-network client retry firing two POST /search calls back to
   back): both requests can pass the `.first() is None` check before
   either commits, then the second `db.commit()` hits the unique
   constraint and raises an unhandled `IntegrityError`. Since
   app/main.py explicitly documents that Task 3D's catch-all
   `internal_error` exception handler has not landed yet ("§13.6...
   Task 3D... once all of Wave 1's routes exist to test it against"),
   this currently surfaces as FastAPI/Starlette's raw default 500, not
   the CONTRACTS.md-shaped envelope — though not a stack-trace leak by
   default. Not blocking since it's explicitly and correctly deferred to
   3D's own gate, but worth Task 3D's rollout re-checking this specific
   route once the global handler lands.

4. MINOR/informational — decisions.py PATCH and saved.py DELETE have no
   optimistic locking; concurrent double-submits on the same PMID from
   the same session are a benign last-write-wins race (no crash, no
   cross-session leakage, no TOCTOU that skips the ownership check
   itself — the `session_id ==` filter is always applied fresh on each
   request). Checked per item 3 of the brief; nothing exploitable found.

5. Nothing else survived scrutiny on the remaining checks:
   - Session scoping is done via SQL WHERE clauses consistently in all
     four route files (decisions.py lines 63-68, saved.py lines 50-58 and
     88-94, queue.py lines 134-136/141-145, search.py as above) — no
     Python-side post-filter-over-broad-fetch pattern found anywhere in
     this task's files.
   - §13.6: confirmed (independently, not trusting tester's prior read)
     that every route's PubMed-facing try/except catches the specific
     `PubMedUnavailableError` class only; the sole broad
     `except Exception` instances in search.py/decisions.py are narrowly
     scoped to `await request.json()` parsing and immediately re-raised
     as `validation_error` — they cannot swallow an unrelated bug
     elsewhere in the route.
   - `retracted` field: purely additive on QueueItem/SavedItem, defaults
     to `False` on the Paper model, and CONTRACTS.md §5 states the
     "false may mean not-yet-known" caveat with an explicit, unambiguous
     directive to the frontend ("render nothing distinctive until the
     flag is confirmed true, never render a false 'not retracted'
     assurance") — this is stronger guidance than a bare caveat and
     substantially reduces (though of course cannot fully guarantee,
     since that's a Task 4A implementation choice) the foreseeable
     trust-problem risk raised in item 4 of the brief.
   - Pagination (§7.9): `retstart`/`retmax` are never taken from request
     input anywhere in these 4 files — `retstart=0` is hardcoded in
     POST /search, and GET /queue's follow-up uses
     `search_session.next_retstart`, a server-maintained integer
     incremented by exactly 20 per successful follow-up fetch, with no
     client-facing parameter to manipulate it. No user-controlled path
     to excessive PubMed calls, an infinite loop, or an over-broad DB
     scan was found.
   - Credential/secret leakage: none found. app/clients.py only
     constructs and lru_caches PubMedClient()/ICiteClient() with no
     credential handling of its own; app/errors.py never interpolates
     `str(exc)` into any client-facing message (confirmed by reading the
     whole file, 66 lines); every logger.warning() call in the 4 route
     files logs only the safe PubMedUnavailableError message or a pmid,
     never a session cookie/token or raw internal exception object.

Verdict: 2 significant findings (missing cross-session tests for
search.py; EFetch parsing failures indistinguishable from genuine 404s,
masking a real-bug class from monitoring), 2 minor findings (SearchSession
TOCTOU explicitly deferred to Task 3D; benign last-write-wins race on
PATCH/DELETE). No blocking findings — nothing found that represents an
active, currently-exploitable session-isolation break, credential leak, or
stack-trace disclosure. Recommend closing significant finding #1 with a
test mirroring the pattern already established for queue/saved/decisions
before treating Task 3A's session-isolation coverage as complete across
all four files, and recommend finding #2 be routed to whoever owns
app/integrations/pubmed.py (Task 1B) or to Task 3D as a candidate for
distinguishing "empty parse result" from "genuine not-found" (e.g. via a
distinct internal signal/log level) so it doesn't silently hide behind a
404.
